Thousands of grade 12 pupils are sitting down for their first matric exam paper. Tshegohaco Moagi talks to Basic Education Minister Angie Motshekga in Johannesburg, Monique Mortlock is in Cape Town and Lethiwe Mdluli is in Durban. #eNCA Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - Basic Education Minister Angie Motshekga visited her former high school, Sekano-Ntoane Secondary School in Soweto on Thursday. Her visit comes as thousands of matriculants sit down for their first exam paper. READ: Ramaphosa wishes matrics well ahead of 2020 exams Speaking to eNCA, Motshekga said she felt emotional considering what teachers and learners had to go through to save the academic year. READ: Class of 2020: Matrics to sit for largest public exam in SA history “From all the reports we’ve been getting…we have no doubt that the system is ready. If anything arises it would have been beyond our control," she said. "But anything that we could manage we’ve put in place to make sure that we have successful exams.” Mothshekga also says the department is prepared. Watch the video above for more details on this story.